Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset appears to have 12 variables and 1599 observations, with each observation corresponding to a red wine sample. 11 of the 12 variables appear correspond to the result of a physicochemical test while the (‘quality’) variable appears to correspond to the result of a sensory panel rating.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest in my dataset is quality rating.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The physicochemical test results will help support the investigation since all the 11 variables are related to characteristics which may affect the flavor of the wine. Some of the variables may have strong correlation with each other.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No I did not create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

No since the dataset presented is already tidy so there was no unusual distributions, no missing values and no need to adjust the data.

Acidity and pH

The pH seems to increase with the lower amount of acidity. Fixed acidity seems to consist of most acidity present in the wine.

## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous y-axis

The pH seems to also increase with the lower amount of citric acid variable, but the relation is not so strong since the citric acidity is at lower concentrations.

The seems to be little or no positive correlation between volatile acidity and pH.

Correlation coefficient:

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The red line connecting the median values shows us the decreasing trend of volatile acidity with quality. Wines with lower volatile acidity content are rated higher in quality.

Plot Two

Description Two

The general trend is that red Wines with higher alcohol content are rated higher in quality as indicated by the sharp increase in quality from 5 to 9. However, the effects of alcohol level on the quality of wines appear to be limited between quality classes 3 and 5.

Plot Three

Description Three

The combined effect of alcohol and volatile acidity on the quality seem to be big. High volatile acidity and low alcohol seem to have lower quality rating. Low volatile acidity and low alcohol seem to be in the middle quality rating categories. Low volatile acidity and high alcohol content seem to have higher quality rating.

Reflection

This project allowed me to apply what I learn about R plotting to explore a real dataset. Since I chose a tidy data sets, no data cleaning or wrangling was needed. However, most of the red wines data points appeared to be at the middle levels than at the low and high ends. The first challenge was to explore what factors might affect the quality of red wine and what variables depend on each other. Plotting variables to predict red wine qualities was fairly accurate for average wines but extremely inaccurate for bad/excellent wines. Inaccurate prediction of bad and excellent wines may be due variables like citric acid, sulphates, volatile acidity being present in specific amounts.

The number one factor for determining an excellent red quality appeared to be Alcohol content.In order for alcohol to take over, however, Citric acid and sulphates needed to be in specific amounts. Large amounts of Volatile acidity seemed to make a wine bad under any circumstances.

Biases in the wine tasters’ preferences seemed to have been a weaknesses since expert wine tasters tend to look for different things in wine than the average person.
